{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed global P95 thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) across the full metric series and filtered metric data to the incident window. The compact per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) aggregate table showed many components with 2 exceedances in the 25-point window (exceed_ratio ~0.08). However, these aggregates do not tell us whether exceedances form consecutive runs (faults) or are isolated spikes. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must now identify consecutive anomalous sub-series (fault identification). To avoid flagging isolated spikes, we'll first search for faults defined as >=3 consecutive points exceeding the global P95. If none appear, we will relax the criterion in a follow-up step.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the in-kernel tables comp_kpi_thresholds and metric_window, detect consecutive anomaly runs per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in the incident window as follows and store the full result as metric_fault_runs in kernel variables. Return only a compact summary table (max 20 rows) and the total number of runs detected.\n1) Join metric_window with comp_kpi_thresholds to get P95 per row. 2) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), sort rows by timestamp_dt and compute a boolean column 'exceed' where value > P95. 3) Identify consecutive True runs (contiguous timestamps with exceed==True). For each run compute: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_ts (ISO UTC), run_end_ts (ISO UTC), run_length (number of consecutive points), max_value_in_run, P95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_run / P95. 4) Filter to runs with run_length >= 3 (i.e., at least 3 consecutive exceedances). 5) Return a compact table of these runs sorted by run_length desc then severity_ratio desc (limit 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_ts, run_end_ts, run_length, max_value_in_run, P95, severity_ratio. Also return the total count of runs found. (If zero runs are found, return an empty table and count=0 so we can relax threshold in next step.)"
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis showed elevated row_count and duration metrics calling multiple candidate services during the incident window, and metric analysis identified short but strong disk I/O spikes on ts-order-service (severity_ratio≈2.68 at 19:25–19:26 UTC) and ts-travel-service (severity_ratio≈1.97 at 19:25–19:26 UTC). Trace error_rate metrics did not increase, suggesting latency/throughput impact rather than request failures. We still need confirmation from logs and raw metric points to decide which service is the root cause (the most downstream faulty service in call chains). The metric evidence points strongest to ts-order-service (largest diskio severity), but we should verify request traffic (log.row_count) and any error_count for ts-order-service and ts-travel-service around 19:24–19:28 UTC before finalizing the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Return compact log and raw metric evidence for ts-order-service and ts-travel-service within the incident window 2024-01-22 19:22:25 → 19:52:25 UTC:\n1) From the in-kernel log DataFrame (log_df), filter to cmdb_id in [\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] and timestamp_dt within the incident window. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) compute: count_in_window, earliest_ts (ISO UTC), latest_ts, max_value_in_window, and return up to 20 rows sorted by max_value_in_window desc.\n2) From the in-kernel metric_window (already filtered to the incident window), extract raw rows for (cmdb_id in [\"ts-order-service\",\"ts-travel-service\"] AND kpi_name==\"diskio\"). Return these rows sorted by timestamp_dt ascending (include timestamp, timestamp_dt, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value) but limit to max 20 rows.\n3) Also return a short summary: for each of the two services give the diskio run(s) previously detected (run_start_ts, run_end_ts, run_length, max_value_in_run, P95, severity_ratio) by reading candidate_metric_fault_runs stored in the kernel (or recompute if needed). \nKeep outputs compact and bounded (<=20 rows each)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, anomaly detection, fault identification and initial trace/log correlation. Metric analysis found short but pronounced disk I/O faults on ts-order-service and ts-travel-service at 2024-01-22T19:25:00→19:26:00 UTC (ts-order severity_ratio≈2.68, ts-travel severity_ratio≈1.97). Trace analysis shows elevated row_count and duration metrics calling both services at ~19:25–19:28 UTC but no error_rate spikes. Log analysis shows high request volume (log.row_count) and no log.error_count increases. According to the localization rules, when multiple service-level faulty components exist we must pick the most downstream faulty service in the trace call chain; if no caller→callee relation exists between them, choose the service with the largest deviation from threshold. Right now we lack explicit evidence of which service is downstream of the other (i.e., whether travel calls order or order calls travel) at the spike minute. To finalize root-cause localization, we need to check traces at the spike timestamps to see if there are direct calls between ts-travel-service and ts-order-service (either direction). If such a downstream relation exists and the downstream service is faulty, that service is the root cause. If no direct relation, ts-order-service shows the stronger deviation and is the likely root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the in-kernel trace DataFrame already filtered to the incident window (trace_window), do the following and return compact results (limit rows to <=50):\n1) Find trace rows at timestamps 2024-01-22T19:25:00+00:00 and 2024-01-22T19:26:00+00:00 where trace_name contains 'to_ts-order-service' OR 'to_ts-travel-service'. Return columns: timestamp, timestamp_dt, cmdb_id (caller), trace_name, value. Limit to 50 rows and sort by timestamp_dt then cmdb_id.\n2) From the full trace_window (entire incident window), compute how many times ts-travel-service appears as a caller for traces whose trace_name contains 'to_ts-order-service' (count), and how many times ts-order-service appears as a caller for traces whose trace_name contains 'to_ts-travel-service' (count). Return these two counts and, if any count >0, return up to 20 example rows for that direction (columns as above).\n(Goal: detect whether ts-travel-service called ts-order-service or vice versa at the spike minutes or elsewhere in the window to determine the downstream faulty service.)"
}

